    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-05-13T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-05-13T00:00:00-05:00" n="1649"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1649">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 819.74/15.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">American Minister</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 51.]</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-05-13">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 13, 1912</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: With reference to the Department’s instruction of
                    April 25, 1912, regarding wireless stations in Panama, a copy of a letter dated
                    April 22 from the Secretary of the Navy is enclosed for your information.</p>
                <p>You are instructed to use your influence against the erection of any radio
                    stations in Panama except those of the Navy Department of the United States, and
                    you will be guided by the Solicitor’s memorandum enclosed with the Department’s
                    instruction No. 43, of April 15, 1912.</p>
                <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Huntington Wilson</hi>.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
